remarks: A mapping (first hypothesis) that is one-to-one (second hypothesis) implies its domain is dominated by its codomain. ` C ` and ` D ` can be read ` C ( x ) ` and ` D ( y ) ` , as can be inferred from their distinct variable conditions.  (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 20-May-2013.)
statement:
dom2.1 $e |- ( x e. A -> C e. B ) $.
dom2.2 $e |- ( ( x e. A /\ y e. A ) -> ( C = D <-> x = y ) ) $.
dom3 $p |- ( ( A e. V /\ B e. W ) -> A ~<_ B ) $.
$d A x y $.
$d B x y $.
$d C y $.
$d D x $.
$d V x y $.
